{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538326"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:26:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:26:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16164"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16164","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16164"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.56,0.15,0.14,0.08,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8855"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87103"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8855","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8855"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16164"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71361"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"188"},{"type":"tags","id":"225"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"3167"},{"type":"tags","id":"4885"},{"type":"tags","id":"4886"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21101"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28908"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28928"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87103","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/87103"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department accompanied by his parent with concerns about his behaviour. Over the past six months, he has become increasingly withdrawn and paranoid, believing his neighbours are monitoring his activities through his computer. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He denies illicit drug use. His parent reports he previously worked as a software engineer but lost his job three months ago due to poor performance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears dishevelled but is afebrile with vital signs within normal limits. His speech is slow with prolonged pauses. When asked about his hobbies, he repeatedly returns to discussing computer surveillance despite attempts to redirect the conversation. When asked to draw different shapes, he draws the same triangle multiple times. During cognitive testing, he continues to provide the same answer to different questions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this patient\u0027s neurological sign?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Perseveration","Echolalia","Palilalia","Logoclonia","Confabulation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient demonstrates features of perseveration in the context of likely first-episode psychosis. Perseveration in psychiatric conditions manifests as the inappropriate continuation or repetition of thoughts, behaviours, or responses despite changes in the situational context or task requirements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerseveration\u003C/strong\u003E in this case is evident in multiple domains: cognitive (fixation on surveillance ideas despite redirection), motor (repetitive drawing), and verbal (providing the same answers repeatedly). While perseveration can indicate frontal lobe dysfunction in neurological conditions, it is also commonly seen in schizophrenia and other psychiatric disorders where executive function is impaired.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEcholalia\u003C/strong\u003E is the automatic repetition of words or phrases spoken by others, which is sometimes seen in autism spectrum disorders or severe psychiatric conditions. This differs from perseveration as it requires an external stimulus that is being copied, rather than the stuck-in-set phenomenon seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPalilalia\u003C/strong\u003E refers to the repetition of one\u0027s own words or phrases with increasing rapidity and decreasing volume. While this involves repetition, it has a characteristic pattern not seen in this case, where the repetition maintains the same volume and pace.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELogoclonia\u003C/strong\u003E is the repetition of the final syllable of a word. This patient is demonstrating thought perseveration rather than syllabic repetition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConfabulation\u003C/strong\u003E is the production of fabricated or distorted memories without conscious intention to deceive. While this can occur in psychiatric conditions, it is distinct from the repetitive pattern of thoughts and behaviours seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of perseveration in this context, combined with paranoid ideation, social withdrawal, and functional decline, suggests a primary psychiatric disorder such as schizophrenia. However, organic causes should still be considered and excluded through appropriate history, examination, and investigations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Perseveration is a neurological sign that can indicate both organic brain disease and psychiatric conditions.","Perseveration in schizophrenia often manifests as repetitive thoughts or behaviours that the patient has difficulty disengaging from.","The presence of perseveration should prompt careful assessment to distinguish between psychiatric and neurological causes."],"references":["Hallion LS, Wright AG, Joormann J, Kusmierski SN, Coutanche MN, Caulfield MK. A five-factor model of perseverative thought. Journal of Psychopathology and Clinical Science. 2022 Apr;131(3):235.","Benjamin JS, Kaplan SJ. Sadock Comprehensive Textbook of Psychiatry."]},"relationships":{"